With this increase in medical comorbidities, there is a risk for polypharmacy (i. e., combinations of medications that may interact or may be unneeded) and adverse events, including delirium (Liang et al.,
            2021
         ). Polypharmacy has been associated with cognitive decline in older adult (Wastesson et al., 
            2018
         ) with psychotropic (e. g., benzodiazepines) and anticholinergic medications (e. g., Benadryl) having particularly strong associations with reversible cognitive impairment (Wastesson et al.,
            2018
         ). Furthermore, chemotherapy agents, anti-hypertensives (beta-blockers), steroids (e. g. Prednisone), and opiates/narcotic analgesics can also adversely
            adversely
          affect cognitive function.

More notable cognitive decline occurs in adults with dementia, otherwise known as major neurocognitive disorder. Dementia affects 57.4 million adults worldwide and is projected to become substantially more prevalent over the next several decades due to population growth and extended lifespans (GBD 2019 Dementia Forecasting Collaborators,
            2022
         ). Major neurocognitive disorder is characterized by non-acute decline in multiple cognitive domains, including memory, recognition, executive functioning, language, and/or motor skills, representing a change from previous functioning and severe enough to interfere with daily life. The most common etiological subtypes are Alzheimer’s disease, Parkinson’s disease, vascular, Lewy body, and frontotemporal dementia (Arvanitakis et al., 
            2019
         ). A key feature of dementia is significant interference with occupational or social functioning.
